Table~\ref{tab:qm9_edgpp} presents the main results on QM9. We highlight three key observations.

\textbf{EDG++ consistently outperforms baselines.} Across all three architectures, EDG++ achieves improvements on 34 out of 36 task-model combinations compared to the no-distillation baselines. The average relative improvements are 3.2\% for SchNet, 9.0\% for Equiformer, and 3.6\% for SphereNet. Notably, Equiformer benefits the most from ED supervision, with improvements exceeding 29\% on $G$ and $U_0$, suggesting that the Transformer-based architecture can more effectively leverage the transferred electronic structure knowledge.

\textbf{EDG++ further improves upon EDG.} Comparing EDG++ (selective distillation) with EDG (naive distillation), EDG++ achieves the best result in the majority of tasks. For SchNet, EDG++ improves over EDG on 10 out of 12 properties, with the exceptions being $\mu$ and $R^2$ where naive distillation retains a slight edge. For SphereNet, EDG++ outperforms EDG on 7 out of 12 properties. This demonstrates that the reliability-aware filtering mechanism effectively identifies and excludes unreliable teacher predictions, leading to cleaner distillation signals in most cases.

\textbf{Property-dependent improvements.} The benefits of ED supervision exhibit clear property dependence. Thermodynamic observables ($G$, $H$, $U$, $U_0$) show the largest average improvement (10.01\% across all models), consistent with their direct relationship to the ground-state electron density via the Hohenberg-Kohn theorem. In contrast, the dipole moment ($\mu$) and zero-point vibrational energy (ZPVE) show smaller or negative improvements for Equiformer ($\downarrow$1.9\% and $\downarrow$3.2\%, respectively), as these properties depend more on charge separation and vibrational modes that are less directly captured by the ED reconstruction objective.

