Tables~\ref{tab:rmd17_energy} and~\ref{tab:rmd17_force} present the energy and force prediction results on rMD17. We observe the following findings.

\textbf{EDG improves all architectures on rMD17.} Consistent with the QM9 results, EDG achieves improvements across SchNet, SphereNet, and ViSNet on the majority of rMD17 tasks. The improvements are particularly pronounced for energy prediction, with SchNet achieving an average improvement of 33.7\% and SphereNet achieving 25.2\%. Force improvements are more modest (SchNet: 1.5\%, SphereNet: 5.3\%, ViSNet: 2.1\%), as force is the gradient of energy and depends on local atomic interactions rather than the global energy distribution captured by ED.

\textbf{EDG++ further improves energy prediction for SphereNet.} EDG++ achieves the best energy prediction on 9 out of 10 molecules compared to the baseline, with notable improvements on aspirin ($\uparrow$31.5\%), salicylic acid ($\uparrow$53.5\%), and benzene ($\uparrow$47.4\%). For force prediction, EDG++ improves on 8 out of 10 molecules. The only molecule where both energy and force degrade is malonaldehyde, which exhibits rapid proton transfer dynamics that may not be well captured by the static-conformation-based ED teacher.

\textbf{Visualization of prediction errors.} Figure~\ref{fig:rMD17_vis} visualizes the absolute prediction error $|y_{pred} - y_{true}|$ for all trajectories in the test set. EDG and EDG++ consistently reduce prediction errors across nearly all conformations, demonstrating that the improvement is not limited to specific molecular geometries but generalizes across the conformational space.

