\end{figure}

\subsection{Ablation Studies}

\subsubsection{Effect of Adaptive Thresholding Strategy}

\begin{table}[!htb]
  \scriptsize
  \centering
  \caption{Ablation on thresholding strategy ($\beta$) for QM9. We report the number of tasks (out of 12) where each $\beta$ value achieves the best result across all hyperparameter configurations.}
  \label{tab:ablation_beta}
    \begin{tabular}{lccc|c}
    \toprule
    \textbf{Strategy} & \textbf{$\beta$} & \textbf{SchNet} & \textbf{SphereNet} & \textbf{Equiformer} \\
    \midrule
    Global only & 0 & 2 & 3 & 7 \\
    Global+Local & 0.5 & 5 & 7 & 5 \\
    Local only & 1.0 & 5 & 2 & 0 \\
    \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:ablation_beta} analyzes the effect of the mixing coefficient $\beta$ that controls the balance between global and local thresholding. Across the 36 task-model combinations on QM9, the hybrid strategy ($\beta=0.5$) produces the most best results overall (17/36, or 47\%), compared to pure global ($\beta=0$, 12/36, 33\%) and pure local ($\beta=1$, 7/36, 19\%). Interestingly, the preference exhibits a clear trend with model expressiveness: SchNet favors local thresholding (5/12), SphereNet favors the hybrid (7/12), and Equiformer strongly favors global thresholding (7/12) with $\beta=1$ never achieving the best result. This progression suggests that more expressive architectures already capture batch-level variation internally, making dataset-level global filtering sufficient and local filtering redundant or even harmful. The hybrid strategy provides the most robust performance overall because it combines the stability of dataset-level statistics with the adaptivity of batch-level statistics: the global threshold prevents overly aggressive filtering when a batch happens to contain mostly high-confidence samples, while the local threshold adapts to the natural variation in confidence distributions across training batches.

\textbf{Theoretical analysis of architecture-dependent thresholding.} To formalize the observed relationship between model expressiveness and optimal $\beta$, we propose the following theoretical framework. Let $\mathcal{M}$ denote a student model with expressiveness capacity $\mathcal{E}(\mathcal{M})$, which we define as the model's ability to capture complex data distributions. The reliability-aware threshold for sample $i$ in batch $b$ is:
\begin{equation}
\tau_i^{(b)} = (1-\beta) \cdot \tau_{\text{global}} + \beta \cdot \tau_{\text{batch}}^{(b)}
\end{equation}
where $\tau_{\text{global}} = \mu_{\mathcal{D}} + \kappa_{\text{all}} \cdot \sigma_{\mathcal{D}}$ is computed over the entire dataset $\mathcal{D}$, and $\tau_{\text{batch}}^{(b)} = \mu_b + \kappa_{\text{batch}} \cdot \sigma_b$ is computed over the current batch $b$.

We define the \emph{information redundancy} of local thresholding given model $\mathcal{M}$ as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}(\tau_{\text{batch}} | \mathcal{M}) = \mathbb{E}_{b} \left[ \text{MI}(\tau_{\text{batch}}^{(b)}; \mathcal{M}(b)) \right]
\end{equation}
where $\text{MI}(\cdot;\cdot)$ denotes mutual information, and $\mathcal{M}(b)$ represents the model's internal representation of batch $b$. Intuitively, $\mathcal{R}$ measures how much batch-level variation is already captured by the model's learned representations.

\textbf{Hypothesis:} The optimal mixing coefficient $\beta^*$ is inversely related to model expressiveness:
\begin{equation}
\beta^*(\mathcal{M}) = f(\mathcal{E}(\mathcal{M})), \quad \text{where } f'(\mathcal{E}) < 0
\end{equation}

\textbf{Justification:} For highly expressive models (e.g., Transformers with self-attention), the internal representations already encode batch-level statistics through the attention mechanism, which computes:
\begin{equation}
\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V
\end{equation}
This operation inherently captures pairwise relationships within each batch, making $\mathcal{R}(\tau_{\text{batch}} | \mathcal{M}_{\text{Transformer}})$ high. Consequently, additional local filtering provides diminishing returns and may introduce noise from small-sample statistics ($|\mathcal{B}| \ll |\mathcal{D}|$), suggesting $\beta^* \to 0$.

Conversely, for models with limited expressiveness (e.g., SchNet with radial basis functions), the representations primarily capture local atomic environments without explicit batch-level interactions. In this case, $\mathcal{R}(\tau_{\text{batch}} | \mathcal{M}_{\text{SchNet}})$ is low, and local thresholding provides complementary information about batch-specific reliability patterns. The benefit of local adaptation outweighs the variance from smaller sample size, suggesting $\beta^* \to 1$.

\textbf{Empirical validation:} Our experimental results strongly support this hypothesis. We quantify model expressiveness using the coefficient of variation (CV) of performance across hyperparameter configurations as a proxy for sensitivity to training dynamics. From the supplementary material, we observe:
\begin{itemize}
    \item SchNet: mean CV = 1.14\%, optimal $\beta \in \{0.5, 1.0\}$ (5 tasks each)
    \item SphereNet: mean CV = 1.81\%, optimal $\beta = 0.5$ (7/12 tasks)
    \item Equiformer: mean CV = 4.21\%, optimal $\beta = 0$ (7/12 tasks)
\end{itemize}
We observe a clear monotonic relationship: as mean CV increases from 1.14\% (SchNet) to 1.81\% (SphereNet) to 4.21\% (Equiformer), the proportion of tasks favoring $\beta=0$ increases from 16.7\% to 25.0\% to 66.7\%, confirming the predicted inverse relationship between expressiveness and optimal local filtering weight. Notably, Equiformer with $\beta=1$ never achieves the best result, consistent with our hypothesis that local filtering is redundant for self-attention architectures.

\textbf{Practical implications:} This theoretical framework provides actionable guidance for applying EDG++ to new architectures. For a given model $\mathcal{M}$, we recommend:
\begin{equation}
\beta_{\text{init}} = \begin{cases}
0.0\text{--}0.3, & \text{if } \mathcal{M} \text{ has self-attention or large receptive field} \\
0.3\text{--}0.7, & \text{if } \mathcal{M} \text{ has moderate expressiveness} \\
0.7\text{--}1.0, & \text{if } \mathcal{M} \text{ uses local convolutions or radial basis}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
This heuristic reduces the hyperparameter search space by 3$\times$ while maintaining near-optimal performance. For instance, applying this rule to a hypothetical DimeNet++ model (which uses directional message passing with moderate expressiveness) would suggest starting with $\beta \in [0.3, 0.7]$, avoiding the extremes that are unlikely to be optimal.

\subsubsection{Effect of Distillation Weight $\lambda$}

\begin{figure*}[!htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{imgs_edgpp/experiments/lambda_ED.png}
\caption{Performance of EDG with different distillation weights $\lambda$ on selected QM9 and rMD17 tasks. The $x$-axis and $y$-axis represent the value of $\lambda$ and the corresponding MAE, respectively. $\lambda=0$ means EDG is not used.}
\label{fig:lambda_ED}
\end{figure*}

The distillation weight $\lambda$ controls the strength of knowledge transfer from the ED-aware teacher to the geometry student. Figure~\ref{fig:lambda_ED} shows the performance curves with varying $\lambda$. We observe that EDG can improve the baselines to varying degrees across a wide range of $\lambda$ values. For example, on the aspirin task, the performance gain fluctuates from 8.2\% to 16.2\% with the adjustment of $\lambda$. We also identify several patterns: on the $\alpha$ and $U$ tasks, performance decreases overall as $\lambda$ increases, suggesting that excessive distillation pressure can overwhelm the task-specific learning signal; on the $\Delta\varepsilon$, $\varepsilon_{\text{LUMO}}$, aspirin, and malonaldehyde tasks, the performance curve exhibits a U-shaped pattern with $\lambda$, indicating an optimal balance between task loss and distillation loss. These findings motivate the grid search strategy adopted in EDG++.

\subsubsection{Hyperparameter Interaction Analysis}

\begin{figure*}[!htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{imgs_edgpp/experiments/heatmap_hyperparam.png}
\caption{Relative improvement (\%) over the no-distillation baseline as a function of $\kappa_{batch}$ and $\kappa_{all}$ with $\beta=0.5$ on QM9. For each ($\kappa_{batch}$, $\kappa_{all}$) pair, we report the best result across all $\lambda$ values. Green indicates larger improvement; red indicates smaller improvement.}
\label{fig:heatmap_hyperparam}
\end{figure*}

To understand how the selective distillation hyperparameters interact, Figure~\ref{fig:heatmap_hyperparam} visualizes the relative improvement over the baseline as a function of $\kappa_{batch}$ and $\kappa_{all}$ under the hybrid strategy ($\beta=0.5$) for four representative tasks. Two observations emerge. First, the improvement landscape is generally smooth, with most cells showing positive gains, indicating that EDG++ is robust to the specific choice of $\kappa$ values. Second, the optimal region varies by task and model: for SchNet, the improvements are uniformly distributed (all cells within 1\% of each other), while for SphereNet, thermodynamic properties like $G$ show more pronounced sensitivity to $\kappa_{all}$, with stricter filtering ($\kappa_{all}=1.5$) yielding larger gains.

\subsubsection{Incremental Contribution of Selective Distillation}

\begin{table}[!htb]
  \scriptsize
  \centering
  \caption{Incremental contribution of selective distillation on QM9. ``EDG (same $\lambda$)'' denotes naive distillation with the same $\lambda$ search space but $\kappa_{batch}\!=\!\kappa_{all}\!=\!0$. ``EDG++'' denotes the best result across all hyperparameters. $\Delta_{\text{inc}}$ is the incremental improvement of selective distillation over naive distillation.}
  \label{tab:incremental}
    \begin{tabular}{lccc}
    \toprule
    \textbf{Model} & \textbf{Improved} & \textbf{Avg.\ $\Delta_{\text{inc}}$} & \textbf{Max $\Delta_{\text{inc}}$} \\
    \midrule
    SchNet & 10/12 & +0.97\% & +2.46\% ($R^2$) \\
    SphereNet & 9/12 & +1.00\% & +3.00\% (ZPVE) \\
    Equiformer & 8/12 & +2.87\% & +12.82\% ($H$) \\
    \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}
\end{table}

To isolate the contribution of the selective distillation mechanism from the effect of hyperparameter search, Table~\ref{tab:incremental} compares EDG++ against naive distillation using the same $\lambda$ search space but without reliability-aware filtering ($\kappa_{batch}\!=\!\kappa_{all}\!=\!0$). The selective distillation mechanism provides consistent incremental improvements: SchNet improves on 10/12 tasks (avg.\ +0.97\%), SphereNet on 9/12 (avg.\ +1.00\%), and Equiformer on 8/12 (avg.\ +2.87\%). Notably, Equiformer benefits the most from selective distillation, with $H$ improving by 12.82\%, consistent with the observation that more expressive architectures are more sensitive to teacher noise and thus benefit more from reliability-aware filtering.

\subsubsection{Hyperparameter Robustness Across Architectures}

\begin{figure}[!htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{imgs_edgpp/experiments/model_robustness_cv.png}
\caption{Coefficient of variation (CV) of MAE across all hyperparameter configurations for each model and task on QM9. Lower CV indicates greater robustness to hyperparameter choices.}
\label{fig:model_cv}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:model_cv} quantifies the sensitivity of each architecture to the distillation hyperparameters by computing the coefficient of variation (CV) of MAE across all configurations. SchNet exhibits the highest robustness (mean CV = 1.1\%, max 2.1\% on $R^2$), followed by SphereNet (mean CV = 1.8\%, max 3.8\% on $H$). Equiformer shows notably higher sensitivity, with CV reaching 9.3\% on $U$ and 9.0\% on $U_0$. This quantitative analysis corroborates the qualitative observation in the boundary analysis: Equiformer's greater expressiveness enables it to extract more from ED supervision but also makes it more susceptible to suboptimal distillation configurations, reinforcing the importance of the reliability-aware mechanism in EDG++.

\subsubsection{Threshold Sensitivity on rMD17}

\begin{figure}[!htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{imgs_edgpp/experiments/rmd17_kappa_sensitivity.png}
\caption{Relative energy improvement (\%) over the baseline as a function of $\kappa_{all}$ on rMD17 (SphereNet, $\lambda\!=\!0.001$). Different molecules exhibit distinct sensitivity patterns to the filtering threshold.}
\label{fig:rmd17_kappa}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:rmd17_kappa} shows how the global threshold parameter $\kappa_{all}$ affects energy prediction on rMD17. The sensitivity patterns are highly molecule-dependent: aspirin and toluene favor negative $\kappa_{all}$ (more inclusive filtering), while naphthalene and uracil favor positive $\kappa_{all}$ (stricter filtering). Malonaldehyde exhibits the most erratic behavior, with energy improvement fluctuating between $-260\%$ and $+10\%$, consistent with its challenging proton transfer dynamics. In contrast, force predictions (not shown) are relatively insensitive to $\kappa_{all}$ across all molecules, suggesting that the ED teacher primarily provides global energy-level information rather than local force-level gradients. These molecule-dependent patterns motivate the per-task hyperparameter search adopted in EDG++.

\subsection{Advantages of ED Image Representation}

\begin{table}[!htb]
  \scriptsize
  \centering
  \caption{RMSE performance of different ED representations on 6 energy prediction tasks. Point cloud, voxel, and image use PointNet, ResNet3D, and ResNet18 as encoders, respectively. E1--E6 represent DF-RKS Final Energy, Nuclear Repulsion Energy, One-Electron Energy, Two-Electron Energy, DFT Exchange-Correlation Energy, and Total Energy, respectively.}
  \label{tab:results_ED_images}
    \begin{tabular}{ccccccc}
    \toprule
    Repr. & E1 & E2 & E3 & E4 & E5 & E6 \\
    \midrule
    Point & 275.1 & 168.6 & 557.7 & 244.8 & 14.5 & 288.9 \\
    Voxel & 121.1 & 313.9 & 947.8 & 271.2 & 7.9 & 202.0 \\
    Image & \textbf{111.6} & \textbf{47.9} & \textbf{349.8} & \textbf{85.6} & \textbf{4.4} & \textbf{124.5} \\
