\end{table}

To validate the proposed multi-view RGB-D image representation, we compare it against point cloud and voxel representations on 6 energy-related prediction tasks. We sample 10,000 molecules from the 2 million DFT data and use the same experimental settings with an 8:1:1 train/validation/test split. As shown in Table~\ref{tab:results_ED_images}, the image-based representation achieves the best performance on all 6 tasks with relative gains ranging from 7.8\% to 71.6\%, demonstrating that 2D multi-view images are more effective than 3D representations for encoding ED information while being resolution-independent.

\subsection{Visualization of ImageED}

\begin{figure}[!htb]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{imgs_edgpp/experiments/ImageED_output.png}
\caption{Visualization of ImageED reconstruction. ImageED generates high-quality ED images compared to the originals. Removing the restoration prediction task ($\mathcal{L}_{RP}$) limits the understanding of local pixel-level features.}
\label{fig:vis_ImageED}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:vis_ImageED} shows the reconstruction quality of ImageED. We find that ImageED can faithfully reconstruct ED images compared to the originals, indicating that it effectively learns ED-related knowledge from the multi-view RGB-D images. Furthermore, removing the restoration prediction task (ImageED w/o $\mathcal{L}_{RP}$) degrades the reconstruction of local pixel-level details, confirming the importance of both pretext tasks in ImageED.

\subsection{Boundary Analysis}

While EDG/EDG++ achieves improvements on the majority of tasks (34/36 on QM9, 17/20 on rMD17), we identify specific scenarios where the current framework reaches its boundaries, providing insights into when ED supervision is most and least effective.

\textbf{Property type matters.} On QM9, the two tasks where EDG++ does not improve over the baseline for Equiformer are the dipole moment ($\mu$, $\downarrow$1.9\%) and zero-point vibrational energy (ZPVE, $\downarrow$3.2\%). The dipole moment depends primarily on charge separation, which requires precise spatial localization of partial charges rather than the global ED distribution. ZPVE depends on vibrational modes of the potential energy surface, which are second-order properties not directly captured by the ground-state ED reconstruction objective. More broadly, grouping QM9 tasks by physical category reveals a clear hierarchy: thermodynamic properties ($C_v$, $G$, $H$, $U$, $U_0$) achieve the largest average improvement (8.51\%) with moderate hyperparameter sensitivity (mean CV = 3.2\%), electronic properties ($\alpha$, $\Delta\varepsilon$, HOMO, LUMO, $\mu$, $R^2$) show consistent but smaller gains (3.30\%, CV = 1.3\%), and the vibrational property (ZPVE) benefits the least (1.18\%, CV = 1.2\%). This hierarchy aligns with the Hohenberg-Kohn theorem: thermodynamic observables are direct functionals of the ground-state electron density, while vibrational properties depend on second-order derivatives of the potential energy surface.

\textbf{Molecular dynamics complexity.} On rMD17, malonaldehyde is the only molecule where both energy and force predictions degrade with EDG++. Malonaldehyde undergoes rapid intramolecular proton transfer, resulting in a delocalized electronic structure that fluctuates significantly across conformations. The static-conformation-based ED teacher, which processes each conformation independently, may not fully capture these dynamic electronic effects. This suggests that extending the framework to account for conformational dynamics could further improve performance on such challenging systems.

\textbf{Architecture dependence.} The magnitude of improvement varies across architectures. On QM9, Equiformer shows the largest average improvement (9.0\%) but also the only two degradation cases, while SchNet shows the most consistent improvement (all 12 tasks improved, average 3.2\%). This suggests that more expressive architectures can leverage ED knowledge more effectively but are also more sensitive to the quality of the distillation signal, further motivating the reliability-aware approach of EDG++.

\subsection{Computational Cost Analysis}

\begin{table}[!htb]
  \scriptsize
  \centering
  \caption{Training cost of the distillation stage on a single NVIDIA H200 GPU. ``Epochs'' and ``Time/epoch'' denote the number of training epochs and average wall-clock time per epoch, respectively. ``Time/run'' is the total time for one hyperparameter configuration. ``\#Configs'' is the number of configurations in the grid search. Note that EDG++ introduces no additional parameters or forward passes beyond EDG; the only overhead is the reliability score lookup, which is negligible.}
  \label{tab:compute_cost}
    \begin{tabular}{llcccc}
    \toprule
    \textbf{Dataset} & \textbf{Model} & \textbf{Epochs} & \textbf{Time/epoch} & \textbf{Time/run} & \textbf{\#Configs} \\
    \midrule
    \multirow{3}{*}{QM9}
    & SchNet & 1000 & $\sim$64s & $\sim$18h & 45 \\
    & SphereNet & 1000 & $\sim$127s & $\sim$35h & 45 \\
    & Equiformer & 300 & $\sim$482s & $\sim$40h & 45 \\
    \midrule
    rMD17 & SphereNet & 1000 & $\sim$166s & $\sim$46h & 7 \\
    \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}
\end{table}

Table~\ref{tab:compute_cost} summarizes the computational cost of the distillation stage. The per-epoch overhead of EDG++ over the no-distillation baseline is minimal ($<$5\%), as the reliability-aware filtering only involves a scalar comparison per sample using pre-computed reliability scores. The dominant cost is the grid search over hyperparameters: for QM9, each model requires 45 configurations (3 $\lambda$ values $\times$ 15 $(\kappa, \beta)$ combinations) per task, totaling $\sim$9.6k, $\sim$19.0k, and $\sim$21.3k GPU-hours for SchNet, SphereNet, and Equiformer, respectively. For rMD17, SphereNet requires 7 $\kappa_{all}$ values per molecule, totaling $\sim$3.1k GPU-hours. All experiments were conducted on 8$\times$ NVIDIA H200 GPUs. In practice, the grid search can be substantially reduced by first identifying a good $\lambda$ on a representative task and then only searching over $(\kappa, \beta)$, which would reduce the search space by 3$\times$.

